 here to win an argument or crown a faction; we are here to keep a city that has survived on careful cups and counted drafts. I have built condensers that taught stone to sweat, and I have seen people use that sweat as leverage until neighbors felt like debts instead of kin. I will not bless a rite that can be twisted into a weapon, not by the Ledger, not by the Syndic, not even by the grief of the Covenant when thirst burns. You carry the notes and the temper to hear where metal thins and where law frays, and I am asking you to braid them so that when we lean our full weight on them they hold without strangling. If the Spire asks a price that spends the poor first, we step back together and choose dimness over harm, because light that costs justice is a counterfeit sun. Remember the founders’ block beneath your hands and the Oris shard that shows consequences; remember that a vow is a machine we must be able to maintain.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Tallea Miranth\", \"lines\": \"I will open the chamber as if I were untying a trusted friend who woke bound, and I will touch nothing until the hum says it is ready to be touched. Water, wind, and heat will be timed together, shared rather than stolen, counted without silencing the breath that gives the count meaning. I will lay the copper ligatures like gentle arteries, and I will set the memory-stone to listen, not to pry, so that the city hears itself as it was promised to be. The founders’ block will stand where law can see it, and the Oris mirror shard will face the prism so that our ambition meets its reflection before it becomes a force. If the note we call down sharpens into a blade, I will sheath it, and if the price climbs beyond what the poor can pay, I will close my hands and accept the dimming until we learn the safer cadence. I will not let my hunger for the missing note make a famine of trust, and if I fail, I will fail openly so the city can correct me rather than choke on a hidden flaw.\"},\n        {\"